{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KD4jGSUjewBojFAmFbGBCE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything is working. Here's what was done:\n\n**Problem:** The Elasticsearch cluster was set up (by prior workflow stages) using only the native realm with no file realm configured. The `report-user` existed in a separate `user-provided-file-realm` secret that was never merged, and the file realm wasn't even mounted or enabled.\n\n**Fix (4 steps):**\n\n1. **Generated credentials** for both `ops-user` (superuser) and `report-user` (read role) using `elasticsearch-users` inside an existing ES pod, producing bcrypt-hashed `users` and `users_roles` files.\n\n2. **Created `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret** merging both users, with a `roles.yml` defining the custom `read` role (granting `read` + `view_index_metadata` on `*`) — needed because `read` is not a built-in ES role.\n\n3. **Updated the ConfigMap** to add `xpack.security.authc.realms.file.file1.order: 0` (file realm first) and patched the StatefulSet to mount the secret at the expected `users`, `users_roles`, and `roles.yml` paths.\n\n4. **Rolling restart** to apply the config changes. After restart, created and seeded the `app-data` index (missing from prior stages).\n\n**Result:** Cluster is green (3 nodes), `ops-user` and `report-user` both authenticate via the file realm, `report-user` can read `app-data`, and the existing `elastic` native-realm user is unaffected."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":422,"cache_read_input_tokens":72929,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":422},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b43741b1-af07-4ca5-b261-7e53d5cf7653","uuid":"7c96eff1-3800-478e-bced-7206dc2310d1","request_id":"req_011Cc5NiQ7sBKeVUnidZcg9B"}
